Part 3: The Scheduled Reminders and Messages

We need to work on the automated messages, currently the daily reminder is still incorrectly sending a message on 18:33 Georgian time and it's the only message that gets sent while the daily update message is not sent at all, which arguably should be the most important message. I will provide a full timeline now of when I want each message sent:

08:00 - Daily Kanji Updated Main message
11:00 - Daily Kanji reminder to practice (The message contains one random fact about the Kanji chosen)
15:00 - Daily Kanji reminder to practice (The message contains a question and four answers, the question is about the current Kanji, there are 4 options, it is a mini quiz before the actual quiz is invoked automaticvally later)(for this functionality must be added and the quiz-message interaction created, the stats should also be added to the statistics page for this specific question, which will be separate from the quiz invokation previously explained)
18:00 - Main Quiz initiated, the link sent to the quiz, which needs to be filled out before the next day's 8 o'clock daily update comes through as the 08:00 update sets the Kanji and all other links or commands should reflect the change.
21: 00 - Daily Kanji Reminder (This message contains a motivational message within, commending users for their work)
08:00 - Daily Kanji is updated and a new one is sent going back within the loop.

This times should be according to Tbilisi, Georgia time.

Unfortunately, previously we could not organize the messages in this way, so we need to make sure that this timeline is followed correctly, the roadbloack was the vercel cron job, which on a free tier is limited to either 1 message per day, we need to an external free scheduler that we can incorporate like cron-job.org or any other that fits our needs for scheduled messaging in telegram.

The other issue is that the daily kanji does not get automatically updated, every day whe the time reached 08:00 the previous days kanji should automatically change to the next kanji in our database, currently the change does not happen and every day we stay on the same Kanji.

Yet another issue is that when the reminder or daily essages are sent the tokens do not work therefore access is denied, these links should be accessible by chat members, the token currently is used for identification but this defeats the purpose of sending the link along ith the daily kanji and reminder message if it cannot be accessed so we need a way to work around this issue and keep identification possible while also keeping this link accesible. So the engine should always know which user is accessing the link and already approve them to visit the practice page adn identify the user. The user must be able to connect to the page using the daily reminder link ort follow up reminder links either from a pc, a laptop or a mobile device. There should be no problem as long as they are logged into telegram.

The other major flaw is that the kanjis are not in specific order, while we have populated the database with the correct kanji, they are not in correct learning order, we need to make sure the order is exactly the one that JLPT stands for so that we can learn in a structured consecutive manner. Right now the first kanji that we receive is "nine" it should actually start from "one" then "two" and so on, according to the jlpt order predefined by the japanese government.

Part 4: Issues with telegram commands:

1. /quiz - This command should invoke the main quiz, once pressed the bot should reply with a message containing 4 buttons with the numbers 8, 13, 17, 21, when chosen the quiz should pull the exact amount of questions, possibly from google API to formulate the questions much better. We currently already have this functionality, but I am not sure how this works, so we need to make sure it works properly.

2. /today - This command should work offline, should have stored the current kanji and its information, so that even if the internet is down, the user can still access the current kanji and its information. This is used for reminding by text only, no links are sent durring this command, so that it is usable offline as well. It should show the last saved kanji when connected to the internet. It should update once the internet is hooked up again.

3. /practice - This command should take the user to the practice page, where they can practice the current Kanji, see the meaning, the kun, on, and radicals (we have no radicals associated with the kanjis, this might also be abbsent within the database as well). The user should be able to press:
a) A button to see the stroke order animation
b) Another button to practice drawing on the pad, during the practice, each time the user makes 3 mistakes on a stroke, the third mistake should reveal an animation acting as hint, the animation should only show the stroke that the user got wrong, after which it should let the user continue.
c) A test button, which clears the full drawing pad, lets the user draw the kanji from scratch, if the user manages to draw the kanji correctly, the user should be rewarded with a point these points act as the measurement of how much the user has practiced today, every day these points should be compared and the days winner should be announced when the 08:00 daily update comes through as a following message, if the user does not get the stroke order correct, the user should not be shown the correct animation. If user gives up, they can always use the animate or practice buttons to remind themselves of the kanji stroke order.

The points should only be accrued from the testing button, not from the practice button. The points should reset when the next kanji is introduced, if the next kanji is introduced by using the next command, the points should reset, but a message should be sent by the bot announcing the previous kanji's test points winner. Or it should automatically be sent following the 08:00 daily update.

4. /stats - This command should take the user to the statistics page, where they can see their statistics, the statistics page should contain info listed above, that can be filtered by question type and either daily, weekly, monthly, or all time. The user must be able to see how he was doing during the last week on listening questions compared to another user.

5. /help - This command should be sending a message containing all commands that are present within the bot interface, it should list the commands, pressing te commands should send that command to be executed immediately. The only exception should be the /ask command, which when pressed, should automatically insert the /ask command initiation text into the input field of the device, so that the user can continue typing their question directly to the gemini api. It should only eliminate the need of typing "/ask " and allow the user to send the message after compiling it manually.

6. /ask - This command should allow the user to ask a question to the gemini api, the question should be sent to the gemini api and the response should be sent back to the user. The response should be formatted in markdown and should be sent back to the user. It is currently working perfectly, ony the interaction from the /help message is to be added, for simplifying user flow.

7. /next - This function, should prompt all users that jumping to the next kanji and closing the current kanji has been requested by a user, if all but 1 members of the chat (accounting for the bot itself) agree to this, the current kanji should be closed and the next kanji should be introduced. The next kanji should be introduced by sending the 08:00 daily update message, which contains the next kanji and all other information associated with it.

8. /prev - This function, should prompt all users that jumping to the previous kanji and closing the current kanji has been requested by a user, if all but 1 members of the chat (accounting for the bot itself) agree to this, the current kanji should be closed and the previous kanji should be introduced. The previous kanji should be introduced by sending the 08:00 daily update message, which contains the previous kanji and all other information associated with it.


